occurrences.line_text: Hauing his armes and warlike things vndight,
And vndiscerned, forth with him did pas.
Like this wyld man, being vndisciplynd,
Are mortall men so fond and vndiscreet,
Nor doen vndo; (for vowes may not be vaine)
And if he shall through pride your doome vndo,
And eke of powre her owne doome to vndo,
So thought she to vndoe her daughters loue:
Ne done vndoe, yet for to salue his name,
His axe he could not from his shield vndoe.
And widowes ayd, least they should be vndone:
And euer what she did, was streight vndonne.
To make exceeding mone, as they had bene vndonne.
And folly seem'd to leaue the thing vndonne,
But his owne doome, that none can now vndoo.
This doe and liue, else die vndoubtedly.
But she ne would vndressed be for ought,
Where groomes awayted her to haue vndrest.
Vnto his bowre was brought, and there vndrest,
Deepe, darke, vneasie, dolefull, comfortlesse,
Or let him die at ease, that liueth here vneath?
Whose passing price vneath was to be told;
And seemd vneath to shake the stedfast ground.
But his fierce foe his steede could stay vneath,
Heare then, ï¿½ man, the sorrowes that vneath
That seeing good Sir Guyon, could vneath
Vneath is to assure; vneath to wene
Vneath is to assure; vneath to wene
And rich purueyance might vneath be red;
And sith it is vneath to find his haunt,
Through which it was vneath for wight to wade;
And his faire wife, whom honest long he kept vneath.
That who he whilome was, vneath was to be red.
That she vneath discerned, whether whether weare.
Till that vneath they forced were for lacke
Him from his wicked will vneath refrayned;
Whose substance was vneath to vnderstand:
That who he was, vneath was to descry;
With heauie eyne, from teares vneath refrayning,
Since I him lately lost, vneath is to define.
So her vneath at last he did reuiue,
So strongly, that vneathes it can refraine
But this was drawne of six vnequall beasts,
Or daunt vnequall armies of his foes,
Scorning the let of so vnequall foe:
My selfe well wote, and mine vnequall fate;
The which to him both far vnequall yeares,
Marcht in one rancke, yet an vnequall paire:
Likewise vnequall were her handes twaine,
With ods of so vnequall match opprest,
For why, he sayd they all vnequall were,
Subiected hath to my vnequall might;
And with vnequall might doe ouerlay,
By this quite slaine in so vnequall fight:
And lurkt in rocks and caues long vnespide.
For tombling into mischiefe vnespide.
And ioyd his loue in secret vnespyde.
Beholding all, yet of them vnespyde.
The other like a Beares vneuen paw:
With his vneuen wings did fiercely fall
Th'vneuen number for this businesse is most fit.
So forth they traueld an vneuen payre,
Ran towards, to deuoure those vnexpected guests.
But simple true, and eke vnfained sweet,
Friendship professed with vnfained hart,
For deare affection and vnfayned zeale,
For nought he car'd his carcas long vnfed;
He was all armd in rugged steele vnfilde,
Vnfit he was for any worldy thing,
Whose fellowship seemd far vnfit for warlike swaine.
From mothers pap I taken was vnfit:
That yet he was vnfit for bloudie fight:
Me all vnfit for so great purpose she employes.
As one vnfit therefore, that all might see
Vnfit faire Ladies seruice to supply;
And horrour of fowle death for Knight vnfit,
I whose vnryper yeares are yet vnfit
Through thicke and thin, vnfit for any Dame.
To driue you so on foot vnfit to tread,
For him to trouble she it thought vnfit,
Of fowle discourtesie, vnfit for Knight;
And put them all about himselfe vnfit,
She in regard hereof refusde and thought vnfit.
Fit to keepe sheepe, vnfit for loues content:
And made vnfit to serue his lawlesse mindes behest.
Vnfitly yokt together in one teeme,
Vnfitly furnisht with thy bag and booke,
Am now enforst a far vnfitter taske,
Was from those Dames so farre and so vnfitting,
For to vnfold the anguish of your hart:
Ne wist yet, how his talants to vnfold;
Let one word fall that may your griefe vnfold,
In his owne kind he gan him selfe vnfold:
Which chaunge of colour did perforce vnfold,
Yet list them bid their businesse to vnfold,
And dared of all sinnes the secrets to vnfold.
But by that meanes, which fortune did vnfold,
And could the ledden of the Gods vnfold,
Though vaine I see my sorrowes to vnfold,
Therewith much comforted, she gan vnfold
There all her subtill nets she did vnfold,
That her brode spreading wings did wyde vnfold;
And all his disaduentures to vnfold;
That like a rose her silken leaues did faire vnfold.
But will my cares vnfolde, in hope to find
Whose wreathed boughts when euer he vnfoldes,
In this sad plight, friendlesse, vnfortunate,
Euen all the nation of vnfortunate
Offricke and Osricke, twinnes vnfortunate,
I am th'vnfortunate Matilde by name,
Sith cruell fates the carefull threeds vnfould,
With which he thresht out falshood, and did truth vnfould.
O foolish Physick, and vnfruitfull paine,
Where so loose life, and so vngentle trade
That his vngentle hoste n'ote him appeach
Him of vngentle vsage did [re]proue
Ne suffereth it thought of vngentlenesse,
Of vile vngentlenesse, or hospitages breach.
He so vngently left her, whom she loued best.
Me hither sent, for cause to me vnghest,
And her lancke loynes vngirt, and brests vnbraste,
To shame vs all with this, Vngirt vnblest.
Such one was VVrath, the last of this vngodly tire.
Whose cursed vsage and vngodly trade
But makes his God of his vngodly pelfe,
And catching hold of her vngratious tong,
Of all the Gods) where thou vngratious,
Vngratious children of one gracelesse sire,
But went her way; ne her vnguilty age
And eke vnhable once to stirre or go,
Whose feeble thighes, vnhable to vphold
Vnhable their encounter to sustaine;
But for he was vnhable them to fet,
Me first he tooke, vnhable to withstond;
Being vnhable else alone to ride;
Such were these Hags, and so vnhandsome drest:
And gin to pittie her vnhappie state,
The messenger of so vnhappie newes
Vnhappie falles that hard necessitie,
Death is for wretches borne vnder vnhappie starre.
For spoyle of wretches, whose vnhappie cace,
Vnhappie Knight, vpon whose hopelesse state
An hard aduenture with vnhappie end;
In th'heritage of our vnhappie paine:
For on his head vnhappily he pight,
And to him cals, Rise rise vnhappy Swaine,
The wretched woman, whom vnhappy howre
When tidings came to me vnhappy maid,
That we may pitty such vnhappy bale,
Shall giue th'enchaunter his vnhappy hire;
What shall of me vnhappy maid become?
Vnhappy mayd (then answerd she) whose dread
But ah vnhappy houre me thither brought:
Gainst wofull Niobes vnhappy race,
Like as it fell to this vnhappy boy,
But Terpine borne to'a more vnhappy howre,
Vnhappy Squire, what hard mishap thee brought
And made great mone for that vnhappy turne.
As thou vnhappy, which them thence didst chace,
From her vnhastie beast she did alight,
The face of his deare Canacee vnheale;
Threatning vnheedie wrecke and rash decay,
Through which some lost great hope vnheedily,
Then suddeinly both would themselues vnhele,
And himselfe baffuld, and his armes vnherst,
And many knights vnhorst, and many wounded,
A prowd rebellious Vnicorne defies,
Thenceforth eternall vnion shall be made
Vnited all his powres to purge himselfe from blame.
In one alone left hand he now vnites,
Till vniuersall peace compound all ciuill iarre.
Faire heauen with an vniuersall cloud,
Peace vniuersall rayn'd mongst men and beasts,
And this great Vniuerse seemd one confused mas.
Is then vniust to each his due to giue?
Vaine is the vaunt, and victory vniust,
Ne deeme thy force by fortunes doome vniust,
With which th'vniust Atheniens made to dy
And most vniust, that by vnrighteous
And them of their vniust possession depriu'd.
Vntrue to God, and vnto man vniust,
That iudgement so vniust against him had ordayned.
It is so hapned, that the heauens vniust,
And with vniust detraction him did beard;
As authour of vniustice, there to let him dye.
To be vniustly blamd, and bitterly reuilde.
Whom a strong tyrant did vniustly thrall,
And eke thy words vncourteous and vnkempt;
Himselfe with incest of his kin vnkend;
Through enuies snares or fortunes freakes vnkind:
He seemd in hart to harbour thoughts vnkind,
Her truth had staind with treason so vnkind;
And with reproch of carelesnesse vnkind
Here heaped vp with termes of loue vnkind,
For they, how euer shamefull and vnkind,
Reproch despightfull, carelesse, and vnkind;
That inly feeds it selfe with thoughts vnkind,
And wound the soule it selfe with griefe vnkind:
For lending life to me a wretch vnkind;
Therefore vnto her mistresse most vnkind
Of many worst, who with vnkind disdaine
To see th'vnkindly Impes of heauen accurst,
And gan abhorre her broods vnkindly crime,
Vnkindnesse past, they gan of solace treat,
To see th'vnkindnesse of his Hellenore.
As those vnknightly raylings, which he spoke,
A gentle knight with so vnknightly blame:
Yet is not this the first vnknightly part,
To be aueng'd of their vnknightly play.
This knight vnarm'd, with so vnknightly breach
Vnknightly Knight, the blemish of that name,
The foule discourt'sies and vnknightly parts,
And what vnknowen nation there empeopled were.
Of wedlocke to that new vnknowen guest:
Pursew her steps, through wild vnknowen wood;
T'approue the vnknowen purpose of eternall fate.
A new vnknowen mischiefe did from him remoue.
Conueyed quite away to liuing wight vnknowen.
And set it all on fire by force vnknowen,
Clad in a vesture of vnknowen geare,
Vnknowen perill of bold womens pride.
Vnknowen was) whence all this did proceede,
So all that night to him vnknowen she past.
Should die vnknown, & buried be in thanklesse thought.
But wander too and fro in wayes vnknowne,
The danger hid, the place vnknowne and wilde,
That for my sake vnknowne such griefe vnto you grew.
In wayes vnknowne, her wandring knight to seeke,
He led a wretched life vnto him selfe vnknowne.
They let her goe at will, and wander wayes vnknowne.
Sith to thee is vnknowne the cradle of thy brood.
And later times things more vnknowne shall show.
Making her seeke an vnknowne Paramoure,
Were from him hidden, or vnknowne of yore.
Vntill a straunger king from vnknowne soyle
By that same way they knew that Squire vnknowne
And hurt far off vnknowne, whom euer she enuide.
Betwixt vs both vnknowne. So ended Paridell.
For thy, they ought not thing vnknowne reproue,
Yet since he seemed valiant, through vnknowne,
A stranger knight, sayd he, vnknowne by name,
Hast thou in all this time, from him vnknowne
Of Knights and Squires to him vnknowne afore:
Or griefe vnknowne, which he could not discerne:
Of which none is to me vnknowne, that eu'r was seene.
That of the like, whose linage was vnknowne,
At last he met two knights to him vnknowne,
Therewith in haste his helmet gan vnlace,
But thought his armes to leaue, and helmet to vnlace.
And th'other brother gan his helme vnlace,
His shining Helmet he gan soone vnlace,
Bad her old Squire vnlace her lofty creast;
But he refusing him to let vnlace,
With that her glistring helmet she vnlaced;
And her sunshynie helmet soone vnlaced,
By which there sate a knight with helme vnlast,
And leaping to him light, would haue vnlast
Her bow and painted quiuer, had vnlaste
Which when she saw, her helmet she vnlaste,
For thing vnlawfull, that was not his owne:
To lodge with him that night, vnles good cause empeach.
Vnlesse she chaunst their stubborne mouths to twitch;
Threatning to strike, vnlesse he would withstand:
Yet was he meet, vnlesse mine eye did faine,
From which vnlesse some heauenly powre her free
Vnlesse some succour had in time him ouertaken.
Vnlesse that she were continent and chast,
Vnlesse it be perform'd with dreadlesse might.
Vnlesse the heauens them lift to lawfull soueraintie.
(Vnlesse thou in these woods thy selfe conceale,
Vnlesse thou dare for thy deare Ladies sake,
Vnlesse that with his Lord he formerly did fight.
Vnlesse that I were thereunto enforst.
Vnlesse to me thou hether bring with speed
And two were browne, yet each to each vnlich,
So doubly lou'd of Ladies vnlike faire,
Vnlike to men, who euer as they trace,
And also far vnlike conditions has;
All three to each vnlike, yet all made in one mould.
And much vnlike, th'one long, the other short,
That seem'd vnlike vnto his earthly home:
And, though (vnlike) they should for euer last,
There him befell, vnlooked for before,
And let him liue vnlou'd, or loue him selfe alone.
Vnlouely Proteus, missing to his mind
By Priamond, that with vnluckie glaunce,
Vnluckie Mayd to seeke her enemie!
Vnluckie Mayd to seeke him farre and wide,
With loud laments that most vnluckie stound,
He spyde, lamenting her vnluckie strife,
In which his life vnluckily was layd,
His mery oaten pipe, but shund th'vnlucky ground.
(Said he) the which with this vnlucky eye
Vnlucky Squire (said Guyon) sith thou hast
Did weene, vnwares, that her vnlucky lo t
And fethered with an vnlucky quill;
But what are you, whom like vnlucky lot
The mother of vnlucky Marinell,
Too greatly grieue at any his vnlucky case.
And sawst the secrets of the world vnmade,
Now comest thou to rob my house vnmand,
Vnmanly murder, and vnthrifty scath,
Yet being men they did vnmanly looke,
As scorning his vnmanly cowardize:
That hath this day so many so vnmanly shent.
Of so vnmanly maske, in misery misdight.
Saying, that he had with vnmanly guile,
Hast slaine my men in this vnmanly maner,
Vnpeopled, vnmanurd, vnprou'd, vnpraysd,
Vnmard with ragged mosse or filthy mud;
Vpbrayd, for leauing her in place vnmeet,
Madan was young, vnmeet the rule of sway,
And garments loose, that seemd vnmeet for womanhed.
Into that wildernesse for her vnmeet,
After long troubles and vnmeet vpbrayes,
And mou'd amisse with massie mucks vnmeet regard.
Such was that Hag, vnmeet to host such guests,
As bosting in their martyrdome vnmeet.
Found nothing that he said, vnmeet nor geason,
Inueigled him to follow her desires vnmeete.
And loathly mouth, vnmeete a mouth to bee,
Whose other wing, now made vnmeete for flight,
That in this wize, and this vnmeete array,
Vpon a mangy iade vnmeetely set,
And dealt her blowes vnmercifully sore:
Leaue off their worke, vnmindfull of their smart,
Vnmindfull of thy praise and prowest might,
Vnmindfull of his wound, of his fate ignoraunt.
Vnmindfull both of that discordfull crew,
Vnmou'd with praiers, or with piteous thought,
So stood these twaine, vnmoued as a rocke,
And all the world in state vnmoued stands,
Ne once my minds vnmoued quiet grieue,
Vnmyndfull of his vow and high beheast,
Some of borne brethren, prov'd vnnaturall;
She feedes on her owne maw vnnaturall,
And fingers filthie, with long nayles vnpared,
Vnpeopled, vnmanurd, vnprou'd, vnpraysd,
In secret anguish and vnpittied plaint,
Long languishing there in vnpittied paine,
That raskall many with vnpittied spoyle;
Vnplough'D, the which my coulter hath not cleft:
Vnpeopled, vnmanurd, vnprou'd, vnpraysd,
Leaue nought vnpromist, that may him perswade,
Vnpeopled, vnmanurd, vnprou'd, vnpraysd,
There for to find a fresh vnproued knight,
To burne the same with vnquenchable fire,
And wrought in Lemno with vnquenched fire:
And rash Occasion makes vnquiet life.
Troubled with terrour and vnquiet iarre,
In restlesse anguish and vnquiet paine:
Vnquiet Care, and fond Vnthriftihead,
That oftentimes vnquiet strife did moue
Those be vnquiet thoughts, that carefull minds inuade.
High Swale, vnquiet Nide, and troublous Skell;
But when she had with such vnquiet fits
Could sleepe all night, that in vnquiet brest
And weary of this worlds vnquiet waies,
Not throughly heald, vnreadie were to ride.
And his vnready weapons gan in hand to take.
Of Gods, of Nymphs, of riuers yet vnred:
That vnto death had doen him vnredrest,
Had throwne to ground the vnregarded right:
He had not left one limbe of him vnrent:
But with glad thankes, and vnreproued truth,
Before their rage grew to so great vnrest,
At last breakes forth with furious vnrest,
One night, when she was tost with such vnrest,
And fairely did dissemble her sad thoughts vnrest.
Many vaine fancies, working her vnrest;
Faire Britomart in languor and vnrest,
Wrapped in wretched cares and hearts vnrest,
That loue it was, which in his hart lay vnreuealed.
Be vnreueng'd, that calles to you aboue
From rightfull owner by vnrighteous lot,
By riches and vnrighteous reward,
And most vniust, that by vnrighteous
And it vsurped by vnrighteous doome:
The wrongfull outrage of vnrighteous men,
Had vtterly subuerted his vnrighteous state.
With her vnrighteous enemy to fight,
Most shamefull, most vnrighteous, most vntrew,
Were soothly so, and that th'vnrighteous ire
Which sought vnrighteousnesse, and iustice sold,
Grew all afore, and loosely hong vnrold,
They breaking forth with rude vnruliment,
Which when none yeelded, her vnruly Page
To Therion, a loose vnruly swayne;
The most vnruly, and the boldest boy,
Whom soone as that vnruly rablement,
As those vnruly beasts to hold without;
That fierce young mans vnruly maistery;
And as she passed through th'vnruly preace
And ranckling inward with vnruly stounds,
I whose vnryper yeares are yet vnfit
And by good fortune shortly him vnseated.
Vnseemely man to please faire Ladies eye;
Neither vnseemely short, nor yet exceeding long.
Saying it was to Knight vnseemely shame,
What if in euery other starre vnseene
Himselfe he frees by secret meanes vnseene;
Lurckt false Duessa secretly vnseene,
For not thy fault, but secret powre vnseene,
And those two Ladies, their two loues vnseene;
With that her angels face, vnseene afore,
Of things vnseene how canst thou deeme aright,
But his late wounded wing vnseruiceable found.
And shyning blade vnsheathd, with which he ran
Vncomb'd, vncurl'd, and carelesly vnshed;
Their feet vnshod, their bodies wrapt in rags,
Vnto her vew, and company vnsoght;
She comes vnsought, and shonned followes eke.
Had guided her, vnwelcomed, vnsought?
Where he remaines, of all vnsuccour'd and vnsought.
Find remedie vnsought, which seeking cannot fynd.
Who now no place besides vnsought had left,
Her flitting partes, and element vnsound,
Deuices, dreames, opinions vnsound,
But of such subtile substance and vnsound,
So feeble is mans state, and life vnsound,
With breach of faith and loyaltie vnsound,
All change is perillous, and all chaunce vnsound.
Yet doubting least his hold was but vnsound,
Doubting sad end of principle vnsound:
Made him become most faithlesse and vnsound:
Which could redresse, for it was inwardly vnsound.
Must be their bed, their pillow was vnsowed,
With so sweet sence and secret power vnspide,
Then hunt the steps of pure vnspotted Maid:
And pure vnspotted life: so well they say
On cursed tree, of that vnspotted lam,
Pure and vnspotted from all loathly crime,
The wind vnstable, and doth neuer stay.
But euer like her selfe vnstained hath beene tryde.
That oft he made him stagger as vnstayd,
T'afflict the other Saxons vnsubdewd;
Where he remaines, of all vnsuccour'd and vnsought.
But wandreth euer more vncertein and vnsure.
Vnsure to whether side it would incline,
The priuate state, and make the life vnsweet:
All th'East before vntam'd did ouerronne,
Their firie Steedes with so vntamed forse
And liking in her yet vntamed heart procure.
Vnthankfull wretch (said he) is this the meed,
Surfeat, misdiet, and vnthriftie wast,
Vnquiet Care, and fond Vnthriftihead,
Vnmanly murder, and vnthrifty scath,
It called was the quicksand of Vnthriftyhed.
Infernall furies, with their chaines vntide.
But when they thought it fast, eftsoones it was vntide.
And how from thraldome vile they were vntide
Vntill the blustring storme is ouerblowne;
Can neuer rest, vntill it forth haue brought
So wept Duessa vntill euentide,
Vntill the witches speech she gan to heare,
And felly gnarre, vntill dayes enemy
Vntill with loue reuokt from vaine affright,
Vntill Duessa loud to him gan crye;
They sadly traueild thus, vntill they came
Nor leaue his stand, vntill his Captaine bed.
He rousd himselfe full blith, and hastned them vntill.
Vntill they came, where that faire virgin stood;
Vntill that Brutus anciently deriu'd
Vntill a nation straung, with visage swart,
Vntill that Locrine for his Realmes defence,
Vntill he quite had spent his perlous store,
Vntill he came vnto a standing lake;
Vntill they nigh vnto that Gulfe arriue,
Vntill they came in vew of those wild beasts:
Vntill that brasen wall they vp doe reare:
Vntill the hardie Mayd (with loue to frend)
Vntill the closure of the Euening.
Vntill a straunger king from vnknowne soyle
Vntill that it an issew forth may find;
Thus she there waited vntill euentyde,
From the fourth houre of night vntill the sixt;
Vntill such time as noble Britomart
There they I weene would fight vntill this day,
Vntill that they their wounds well healed had,
Vntill another tyde, that I it finish may.
I will deferre the end vntill another tide.
Vntill she came where wonned his Belphebe faire.
Vntill the ripenesse of mans yeares he raught;
Vntill that Talus had his pride represt,
Vntill that Guyon selfe vnto him spake,
But mongst the rest the fight did vntill euening last.
Vntill his owne true loue his freedome gayned,
Vntill she spide the lampe of lightsome day,
Vntill they both doe heare, what she to them will say.
Vntill that state by strength was pulled downe,
Vntill he had her settled in her raine,
Backe to recule; vntill that yron man
Vntill late mischiefe did vppon me light,
Vntill the loue of Lordship and of lands
Vntill a Mantle she for him doe fynd,
Vntill fit time and place he mote espy,
The end whereof Ile keepe vntill another cast.
And sate there still, vntill the flying day
Vntill the damzell gan to wex more sound and strong.
Vntill that, whether wicked fate so framed,
